{{refimprove|date=July 2008}}
[[Image:Seneca-berlinantikensammlung-1.jpg|thumb|[[Double Herm of Socrates and Seneca]] ([[Antikensammlung Berlin]])]]

'''Senecan tragedy''' refers to a set of [[Ancient Rome|ancient Roman]] [[tragedies]]. Ten of these [[Play (theatre)|plays]] exist, of which most likely eight were written by the [[Stoicism|Stoic]] philosopher and politician [[Lucius Annaeus Seneca]]. The group includes ''Hercules Furens'', ''Medea'', ''Troades'', ''Phaedra'', ''Agamemnon'', ''Oedipus'', ''Phoenissae'', ''Thyestes'', ''Hercules Oetaeus'', and ''Octavia''. ''Hercules Oetaeus'' is generally considered not to have been written by Seneca, and ''Octavia'' is certainly not.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Oxford Companion to Classical Literature|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=2014-07-12|ref=1}}</ref> In the mid-16th century, [[Italian humanists]] rediscovered these works, making them models for the revival of tragedy on the [[Renaissance]] stage. The two great, but very different, dramatic traditions of the age — French neoclassical tragedy and [[Revenge play|Elizabethan tragedy]] — both drew inspiration from Seneca. Usually, the Senecan tragedy focuses heavily on supernatural elements.

Although many of the Senecan tragedies adapt the same Greek myths as tragedies by [[Sophocles]], [[Aeschylus]], and [[Euripides]], scholars tend not to view Seneca's works as direct adaptations of the Attic works, as Seneca's approach to the myths differs significantly from the Greek poets and often contains themes familiar from his philosophical writings.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Buckley|editor1-first=Emma|editor2-last=Dinter|editor2-first=Martin|title=A Companion to the Neronian Age|date=2013|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|accessdate=2014-07-12|ref=2}}</ref> It is possible that Seneca's tragic style was more directly influenced by [[Augustan literature (ancient Rome)|Augustan literature]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tarrant|first1=R. J.|title=Senecan Drama and Its Antecedents|journal=Harvard Studies in Classical Philology|date=1978|volume=82|pages=213–263|ref=3}}</ref>

French neoclassical dramatic tradition, which reached its highest expression in the 17th-century tragedies of [[Pierre Corneille]] and [[Jean Racine]], drew on Seneca for form and grandeur of style. These neoclassicists adopted Seneca's innovation of the confidant (usually a servant), his substitution of speech for action, and his moral hairsplitting.

The Elizabethan dramatists found Seneca's themes of bloodthirsty revenge more congenial to English taste than they did his form. The first English tragedy, ''[[Gorboduc (play)|Gorboduc]]'' (1561), by [[Thomas Sackville, 1st Earl of Dorset|Thomas Sackville]] and [[Thomas Norton]], is a chain of slaughter and revenge written in direct imitation of Seneca. (As it happens, ''Gorboduc'' does follow the form as well as the subject matter of Senecan tragedy: but only a very few other English plays—e.g. ''[[The Misfortunes of Arthur]]''—followed its lead in this.) Senecan influence is also evident in [[Thomas Kyd]]'s ''[[The Spanish Tragedy]]'', and in [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Titus Andronicus]]'' and ''[[Hamlet]]''. All three share a revenge theme, a corpse-strewn climax, and The Spanish Tragedy and Hamlet also have ghosts among the cast; all of these elements can be traced back to the Senecan model.

